      "writtenOn": "2020-03-18T14:30:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Thoughts and questions in arbitrary order:\n\nMost of our apps are using \"cloud logging\" which is actually just using glog and relying on Kubernetes to plumb logs into Cloud Logging. The plan is to use the JSON adapter and just dump JSON to stdout for this use case?\n\nTask Drivers are using cloud logging v2 because they don\u0027t run in Kubernetes. I think I\u0027ve expressed elsewhere that I think it\u0027d be nice to add a log connector of some kind and just have them dump JSON as well.\n\nFor running locally, we\u0027d want to not use structured logs, and ideally trim some or all of the prefixes we get with glog.\n\nThe above seems to imply yet another implementation, something like \"raw_logs\" which would just write lines directly to stdout or stderr without any prefixing/changes/etc.  For our apps running in k8s we\u0027d use raw_logs and add the structured logging wrapper if --local was not supplied.  Command line tools intended to be run by humans would use raw_logs directly.  In the short term, non-local, non-k8s apps (does this include Skolo?) would use cloud logging v2 with the JSON adapter.  Longer term, those could also use raw_logs with a log connector to get them into Cloud Logging.  I think that leaves us with three well-defined logging implementations, but I don\u0027t understand the use case for slog.",
      "parentUuid": "f154d3f5_4b0d0452",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 97,
        "startChar": 41,
        "endLine": 97,
        "endChar": 45
      },
      "revId": "79c4295db7d486cb08ca41da0f27bdb6cdaf8c27",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
